##"Diamond Princess" adventure: Cruise Quarantine really in place?

When the Japanese government ordered the quarantine of the diamond princess on February 5 for two weeks, no one could have imagined that more than 630 newly diagnosed cases of pneumonia would be on board the ship with 3,700 people on board.

A month after setting out from Port of Yokohama, the diamond princess is finally starting to send passengers and crew from dozens of countries. After this unprecedented reunion, the people on board are moving into a new and distinct phase:

The confirmed patients and their close contacts travel to medical facilities and specific isolation facilities in Japan, while foreign passengers who test negative for the virus, such as citizens of the United States and Australia, travel by charter flight home for an additional two-week isolation period; Most of the freed Japanese had disbanded at the Yokohama Station, and some had arranged to meet friends at a Sushi restaurant.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Passenger DAXA posted on Twitter his permission to disembark

And for the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare, who had no responsibility or obligation to take the international ship, they still have to answer a question that has been raised many times: Keeping everyone on board for two weeks, is that really the best thing to do?

###Stay with the ship

The "Diamond Princess" set out from Yokohama on January 20 via Kagoshima, Hong Kong and Taiwan, as well as Vietnam. Meanwhile, an 80-year-old passenger who had presented with cough symptoms got off the ferry in Hong Kong on January 25 and was confirmed to be infected with the novel coronavirus on February 1. By this time, a week after the passenger disembarked, the diamond princess had left Okinawa and was on its way back to Port of Yokohama with 2,666 passengers and 1,045 crew.

Although the diamond princess starts and ends in Japan, the ship, which is owned by an American cruise company, flies the British flag and is supposed to be governed by British law under the principle of "flag nationalism" administered by its home country.

The Japan economic news commentary stressed that Japan is not under an obligation under international law to allow cruise ships to dock, perform crew checks and provide life support, that's a judgment given that nearly half of the passengers are Japanese. The commentary quoted a Japanese government source as saying that "the cruise ship could have been refused permission to land" .

Indeed, after the presence of a confirmed patient, Japan may well refuse the diamond princess to dock on the basis of the "circumstances likely to endanger the interests of Japan and Public Safety" referred to in Article 5, paragraph 1, of its exit-entry law. This was the legal basis for the subsequent refusal of Japan to dock the ship, and for the refusal of entry to those who had visited China's Zhejiang Province.

But the Ministry of Health and Labour took over. From Feb. 3 to 4, all the passengers had their temperature taken, and some had blood tests, U.S. Passenger Matthew Smith told interface news. "At 7 a.m. on February 5, the captain told us that because 10 people tested positive for the virus, we would be quarantined by Japanese officials for 14 days, during which time we would have to remain in the cabin. "

Japanese Prime Minister Shinzo Abe said on February 5 at the headquarters of countermeasures, "now in the face of large passenger ships in the collective infection of this new situation, we must take foolproof measures. ".

In the face of the sudden two week quarantine, passengers and crew were unaware that, according to a study released by the Institute of Medical Science after the incident, there was clear evidence that before the ship was quarantined on 5 February, "there has been a significant spread of the new coronavirus on board. ".

Before passengers and crew start to stay in their rooms and wait for orders, Hokkaido University professor SHIPO NISHIPO said Tuesday, citing data analysis from the Institute of Medical Science, inside the ship was a "high-risk environment in which an average of one infected person passed on to five others" .

So, if measures are to be taken to prevent the spread of the virus, why doesn't the Japanese government let everyone leave the ship and stay in an isolation facility on land?

First, the Japanese government has concerns about avoiding the domestic spread of the virus. Kyodo News Agency quoted government sources as saying: "In order to prevent the spread of the [ virus ] in the country, we believe that it is safer to keep all the people in the ship. ". Even if you're told that the initial response is too slow, you're already doing it."

There is also a view within the ministry that the 2009 outbreak of influenza a (H1N1)"led to the allocation of resources to border control measures, resulting in medical institutions become vulnerable" . And about 80 percent of the people on the cruise are foreigners, while only a limited number of Japanese medical facilities are able to accommodate foreigners who do not speak Japanese.

In addition, when the diamond princess docked, Japan's ability to detect the new coronavirus only about 300 times a day. Concentrating efforts on testing everyone on board would probably weaken the ability to do so elsewhere in Japan.

"since there are no large quarantine stations on land that can accommodate a large number of people, [ staying on the ship ] is the appropriate approach, " said Sakurai, a professor at Iwate Medical University who heads the survey team at the Japanese environmental infection society.

###Living in isolation

After the initial chaos, the crew and passengers of the diamond princess lived in routine isolation. Passengers on board will continue to enjoy free Internet and telecommunications services, food and drinks selected from the daily menu will be delivered directly to the isolated cabin, and crew members who have passed the inspection by the Ministry of Health and Labour will continue to perform their duties as required, princess said.

In addition, cruise companies are working closely with leading health authorities to take steps to minimize the importation and spread of infectious disease on board ships and to increase the frequency of environmental disinfection.

At the same time, some passengers have started to share their isolation on social networks, telling Internet users and media around the world what they eat in the morning, lunch and evening, and how they and their companions spend their time grounded.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Origami and Sudoku on board, via Twitter for DAXA

The isolation period, however, was not peaceful and pleasant. If the virus tests positive, passengers and crew will be taken off the ship and sent to Japanese medical facilities. If the test is negative, they will remain on board until the quarantine period is over.

US Passenger Taylor Torres told interface news that he and his wife were first tested for the virus because of flu and cough symptoms before and after boarding the ship and were not informed of the diagnosis. The couple, however, did not receive the announcement from the Health Ministry that their results were negative. Under the limited detection capacity, the ship's owners had to wait for Japan's Ministry of Labor issued a great sadness or joy notice.

Three days before the quarantine (until February 7) , 70 people were confirmed on board; by the Sixth Day (February 10) , the number had nearly doubled to more than 130 confirmed cases. At this time, Chinese Hong Kong passenger Huang Yaxi told the interface news that the masks issued on board the ship had been upgraded from ordinary masks to N95.

The average number of infections has dropped from five to one in the five days since the Hokkaido University asked passengers and crew to remain in their rooms, "and the rate of infection has been reduced dramatically by countermeasures, " said study author Hokkaido University.

On February 17th the province announced that 99 new cases had been confirmed in a single day, the highest number in isolation. As of February 20, a total of 634 people were found infected with the new coronavirus on board, including two passengers in their 80s who died.

With the number of confirmed cases rising sharply, and with more than, workers on board, there is a growing body of observational research suggesting that the isolation on board is inadequate. The New York Times called it an "unprecedented failure" . "Japan's reputation as a world-class player in health care has been tarnished, " a South Korean television critic said

The Institute of Medical Science said that in order to maintain life on board the ship, the crew had to continue to provide services, which led to the crew not being completely isolated as passengers were during the quarantine period.

Sakurai, who has been on board the ship since February 11, found that the N95 masks worn by the crew could easily become overwhelming after 15 minutes, but releasing them could lead to hand-face contact and spread the virus. In addition, the crew manual says to wash your hands with tap water and then alcohol, but if you have water on your hands, the effect will be compromised.

Sakurai noted that with regard to conditions inside the ship, "although basic precautions against infection were taken in accordance with the manual, the crew felt the difficulty of communicating epidemic prevention measures due to differences in countries and languages. ".

As the quarantine period drew to a close, a video released by a medical expert caused even more controversy. Iwata, a professor of infectious medicine at Kobe University, posted a video on YouTube on Feb. 18 of what he saw aboard the Diamond Princess. The video received more than a million views before Iwata deleted itself on February 20.

Iwata said he had worked on infectious diseases for 20 years and had expertise and experience in dealing with Zaire ebolavirus and SARS. Even so, he said the situation on the cruise ship was "really tragic and genuinely terrifying" .

He said there was no "red zone" where the virus could spread and no "Green Zone" where there was no need for protection. Many people did not wear masks and patients with fever would walk directly from their rooms to the infirmary. The man in the quarantine office would suddenly say to him, "Ah, that man who just walked past is a patient. ".

In addition, Iwada said he was lukewarm in his talks with senior officials in the province. He was called off the ship to make a suggestion, and his quarantine permit was revoked. He said Japan did not share China's emphasis on transparency and did not disclose any information on the diamond princess. "If no one goes public, I'll have to do it here. "

But Mikell, who's executive director of Emergency Planning, said on February 18: "The situation on this ship has clearly changed, with the initial decision by the Japanese authorities to quarantine all passengers on board, allowing passengers to remain in an observable environment where they have their own accommodation and everything else. Obviously, under the circumstances, it was much better than having everyone scattered around the world."

###When we get off the ship,

February 19th, the day the Diamond Princess's quarantine period ended. Hundreds of passengers left in turn and boarded the long-lost land. And the Japanese government has begun to explain what Iwada said on the Internet.

An official from the Asahi Shimbun told the newspaper that there were no experts on board and that the statement that "laymen lead the defense of infectious diseases" was incorrect. Health care workers who are familiar with infectious diseases work in the field every day and are instructed to learn to deal with infectious diseases. He stressed that there are structural limitations to being able to do this on a ship like a hospital, where other people try to avoid being in the corridor when transporting infected people.

Princess cruises had previously said the government had provided at least 7,000 face masks and a team of 16 doctors, 12 nurses and medical receptionists.

Earlier on Feb. 20, Fujioka Katsumoto of Japan responded by saying that infection experts had pointed to a variety of topics and were making corrections every day, according to field workers.

In response to Internet claims that the Japanese government pressured Iwata to remove the video, Chief Cabinet Secretary Yoshihide Suga denied the government's intervention at a press conference on the 20th, stressing that "there are experts on board to manage the infection" .

IWADA deleted the video himself on February 20. "after pointing out the problem, the ship's response to the infection has improved a lot, " he said at a televised news conference in Tokyo that afternoon

Iwada said: "When I got on board, the infection control measures in the ship were not sufficient. Yesterday (19 February) I heard from the relevant personnel that the area division in the ship had been thoroughly implemented and the control measures had been greatly improved. " "measures such as the publication of the First National Institute of Medical Science Report on the data on the ship's infected persons also played a role. ".

However, the credibility of several statements were also undermined by the vice minister of High Labor Yukio Hashimoto. He tweeted about the difference between the "Clean Route" and the "dirty route" on the ship, only to be found sharing a spacious atrium in front of the two doors, which were in fact difficult to separate. Hashimoto then deleted the image.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Hashimoto on Twitter

"obviously he deleted twitter, and I'm glad he knows the problem is real, " Iwada said, noting that passengers leaving the ship on the 19th "are still at risk of infection and need to be monitored for two weeks. ". However, a large number of Japanese passengers have taken public transport home, no need to accept additional isolation.

There are only about 1,800 special beds for Infectious Diseases in Japan, Nobuhiko Okabe, director of the health and safety institute in Kawasaki, told the Nikkei on Feb. 12. If patients with mild illnesses also need to be hospitalized, hospitals will soon be full, the mechanism of prioritizing the treatment of critically ill patients is very important.

Sakurai believes that in the case of the United States, where only 300 passengers are returning home on charter flights, isolation at military bases is feasible. But there were too many Japanese on board, and there was no quarantine facility. "that was the reality. ".

The World Health Organization said in Geneva on February 18 that while the initial measures to keep passengers and crew on board were satisfactory, the spread of the infection went beyond expectations. The organization also calls for the continuation of the necessary care for those disembarking from the ship.

"with limited resources, hospitals will always run out of some materials, and if the Tokyo area can handle such a situation, the rest of Japan is not so sure, " said Koji Watada, a professor of Public Health at the International University of Health and Welfare. "The outbreak is likely to continue for at least a few more months, and the government would be well advised to develop a plan for a long-term response. "

"When we look back, it's easy to judge the public health decisions made at that point in time, " says World Health Organization's Mikell.

"This is an unfortunate incident that took place on board the ship, and we are confident that the Japanese authorities and the government receiving these people will be able to track them in an appropriate manner to ensure that they are properly cared for. It's important to study this particular event and see what's causing it to spread to the people on board,"he said.
